{
  "texts": [
    "Mutation testing, a widely accepted standard for evaluating fault detection capability, is deeply integrated into the generation process by frameworks such as MuTAP [32].",
    "This approach identifies mutants that survive initial test runs and feeds this information back to the LLM, explicitly instructing it to generate new tests capable of \"killing\" them.",
    "This elevates the objective from merely increasing code coverage to attaining higher mutation scores; MuTAP achieves a mutation score of 93.57% and detects 28% more real-world bugs than traditional tools like Pynguin [32].",
    "To further improve efficiency, the PRIMG framework incorporates a mutant prioritization module before feeding surviving mutants back to the LLM.",
    "This module utilizes machine learning models to predict the value of each mutant and prioritizes generating tests for those most likely to reveal multiple faults, thereby achieving higher mutation scores at a lower cost [19]."
  ]
}